Hello,

I am preparing a pull request for displaying users's quota used/left. To do so I created a new RemoteOperation copying the GetRemoteUserNameOperation available. However, I am continuously getting 400 Bad Response back from the server, while with a simple Curl everything works nice and smooth. Since with a basic inspection of the headers I couldn't figure out I sniffed my own packets with Wireshark and found the problem:

Working request:
![Working request]
(http://en.zimagez.com/full/d9883644368b3444817defaa1cf6b7547f1cf73079c1da8496d2014e9ccb2aac787fd0f12684c267.php)
http://en.zimagez.com/zimage/rightreq.php

Non working request:
![Not working request]
(http://en.zimagez.com/full/1f425d62cf0d6220817defaa1cf6b754ad1ae9c679685fe24561f540f30997a1787fd0f12684c267.php)
http://en.zimagez.com/zimage/wrongreq.php

If you want to try it out we have a server up and running at 54.77.93.38 user/pass = demo demo .

And finally here is the code I used:

curl that works:
    curl -H "Authorization: Basic ZGVtbzpkZW1v" http://54.77.93.38/ocs/v1.php/cloud/users/demo

Java code that doesn't

      private static final String OCS_ROUTE ="/ocs/v1.php/cloud/users/";

       String url = client.getBaseUri() + OCS_ROUTE + credentials.getUsername();
       get = new GetMethod(url);
       get.addRequestHeader(createAuthenticationHeader(credentials));
       get.setQueryString(new NameValuePair[]{new NameValuePair("format","json")});
       status = client.executeMethod(get);

    private Header createAuthenticationHeader(OwnCloudCredentials credentials){
        Header h = new Header();
        h.setName("Authorization");
        String authString = credentials.getUsername()+":"+credentials.getAuthToken();
        String encodedString = Base64.encodeToString(authString.getBytes(), **Base64.DEFAULT**);
        h.setValue("Basic "+encodedString);
        return h;
    }


The problem are these extra termination characters added that obviously screw everything up. I have no knowledge of the apache commons httpclient, but Google didn't return any known issue.

EDIT: I found the problem. the Android Base64.DEFAULT appends a \n to the end of the string. You must use the .NO_WRAP flag

